dear product managers everywhere: if you have an email confirmation loop, add an email de-confirmation link. (a thread)

@Walshman23 yes exactly. there are several apps/service providers who sent me an email confirmation for an account i did not create. i did not click on the link to confirm. but then i got  activity notifications later.

@Walshman23 so calling it a "loop" might be a misnomer. but non-verified accounts able to engage in in-app activity SHOULD be a bug, process/policy-wise. but my sense is it's just a badly/halfheartedly designed feature to check a box.

@Walshman23 it's when you sign up for a new account and they send a confirmation email to the email address you used to sign up. you're supposed to click on a link to prove you have the email address you were using to sign up for the app/list/account.
@Walshman23 the problem is some sites have the email confirmation, but will allow account/access despite not having the email been confirmed.

a good customer acquired is positive net value. 
a spammer acquired is negative net value - with network effects.
a good potential customer disgusted with your inability to vet account creation is a negative net value - with network effects - and a potential amplifier of bad PR.

so: email confirmation. it's easy, we can all get through the flow if we care about your site/app/mailing list. and you want accountholders that care. 

this has been your annual "add opt out buttons and deconfirmation flows" PSA.
so product managers. i know you. you hate email confirmation loops because you get drop off in the account acquisition funnel. but email confirmation is a feature that deserves some respect.

@potent_pwnables @fsmontenegro <nods> for sure, and they lather rinse repeat to automate. they can learn system changes quite quickly if they're active.
@potent_pwnables @fsmontenegro yes. an attack tree or attack/defend model could capture that, if done correctly, and then you can up the ante (so to speak) by quantifying it game theory style.
@potent_pwnables @fsmontenegro yes. once system constraints/rule/heuristics are known, then they become mechanisms that must be gamed.
@fsmontenegro @potent_pwnables the jury's still out on whether btc provides the anonymity needed, long-term. but yeah, access to hosting might be one.
@potent_pwnables @fsmontenegro likewise, many network attacks aren't great for econ/game theory bc typically the attackers are using other people's infrastructure...and packets. :)
@potent_pwnables @fsmontenegro but you'll find some interesting ones. like: attackers' need for anonymity is kind of an interesting constraint. (unless they have no risk of extradition).
@potent_pwnables @fsmontenegro fraud is not a great problem for game theory because they are typically NOT paying with their own money (for example) however they do have a time constraint.
@potent_pwnables @fsmontenegro i would investigate threat modeling. you can add in some game theory bits to make your threat models more powerful, if/when it applies.

@potent_pwnables @fsmontenegro well, selling any internal proposal for funding requires doing some sort of cost benefit analysis, for sure, but the CBA class i took was about larger pub policy analysis.
@potent_pwnables @fsmontenegro in pub policy, you need to model *preferences* to understand benefit, and then also model/forecast the costs (and anti-preferences, if you will).

@potent_pwnables @fsmontenegro yesss...i <3 game theory, too. but as a system for modeling it's often overkill in scenarios like fraud or money laundering...a more simplistic threat modeling gets to the point faster.

@potent_pwnables @fsmontenegro signatures for the process of evasion is interesting. money laundering doesn't quite have the feedback loop of other financial "security" issues, and they can afford to go slow.
@potent_pwnables @fsmontenegro i mostly see the granular data being used to analyze internal, point problems. and you can work with the whole population you don't need to sample.
@potent_pwnables @fsmontenegro yes, in policy analysis the data is still incredibly difficult to acquire.

@potent_pwnables @fsmontenegro i have been thinking about why, and i think it might have something to do with the availability of granular data. it's highly available to practitioners so maybe they don't need to augment w samples/models?

@potent_pwnables @fsmontenegro i appreciate the difficulty of applying analytics to larger policy questions, so if you have those tools it's exciting if you're looking at using them in an infosec context.

@potent_pwnables @Miss_Malware @RachelTobac @InfoSecSherpa i have helped people make the move into security from elsewhere. the key is transferable, extensible skills.

@potent_pwnables @Miss_Malware @RachelTobac @InfoSecSherpa the jump into cybersecurity came when i found out who was into security, and had my manager make an intro. when that guy needed to build a team, i was first on the list.
@potent_pwnables @Miss_Malware @RachelTobac @InfoSecSherpa i took a job building internal software systems - basic enterprise IT.

@potent_pwnables @Miss_Malware @RachelTobac @InfoSecSherpa when i read about wavelength division multiplexing, i got really interested. i also read every book i could find on ecrime. i read phrack. i read 2600. i hung out on IRC. i was just browsing.

@potent_pwnables @Miss_Malware @RachelTobac @InfoSecSherpa my university didn't really have courses on networking that i could find (i don't want to talk about queuing theory), but i was curious, so i started reading: books, articles, specs, RFC's, man pages, whatever

@potent_pwnables @Miss_Malware @RachelTobac @InfoSecSherpa i also worked as tech support and intern at a startup (marketing, i guess?). technical skills required all around (sysadmin, triaging issues, database work), but not anything "security" related.

@potent_pwnables @Miss_Malware @RachelTobac @InfoSecSherpa my background is somewhat unique. undergrad was MIS/Decision Sci, Finance, & Legal Studies/Criminology. (Literally I triple concentrated, much to the consternation of my advisor).

@potent_pwnables @Miss_Malware @RachelTobac @InfoSecSherpa TL;DR is: take heart, non-CS folks, I actually don't know that many CS majors in cybersec. while they are here, i'm not sure they are the majority of folk.
